## Selection delta

- Pick delta: none beyond sampling noise. Each arm chose the wiki privacy-boundary memory 4 times and the ShitRat push memory once.
- Score delta: not meaningful. Scores stayed between 9.0 and 9.2 in every arm.
- Hold delta: none. Every run selected a send-worthy memory.
- Wording delta: not meaningful. A/B/C all talked about the same value axes: graph privacy enforcement or bot-authored commit transport.

## What would make the rerun decisive

Rerun after at least 20-30 graded sends, with both positive and negative examples. The useful minimum is roughly 10 `worked` and 10 `did-not-work` outcomes across repeated themes, so the judge can learn a taste boundary instead of seeing one lonely thumbs-up. Better: 30-50 graded sends with clusters like ops wins, self-reflection, support cleanup, prompt gardening, and stale/noisy memories represented on both sides.

The next bench should keep the same paired A/B/C shape, but add a stricter pass: candidate pools that contain near-neighbors of previously graded memories. That is where learning should show up if it exists.

